didn't like the character development system.  I like to spend time killing creatures to level my character and gain new attributes/abilities.  Spending gold at a trainer to get levels is fairly lame.  <br><br>And my biggest nag of all, where is the window that displays the target's health! <p><br><br><br><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~slbush/wein.gif" ALIGN="left" ALT="[60 Virtuoso] Ainwein (Wood Elf) <Fellowship of the Blue-Eyed Monkey>"><br><b>Virtuoso</b><br><i>Ayonae Ro</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uphixer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Phixer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Journeyman</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(8/7/02 3:40:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Neverwinter Nights</span><hr size=1> Well, having played the crap out of both games, I'll put in my analysis.<br><br>Neverwinter Nights: <br>   Standard 3rd edition RPG fare.<br>   Predictable in storyline, plot, and method of level increase (we're all familiar with the 'kill stuff to get better' mentality).<br>   Equipment and spells and gameplay that we're relatively familair with (especially those of us that play 3rd edition D&amp;D).<br>   Quests are usually confined to small areas not requiring extensive travel or exploring to complete.<br>   There is no process by which a player (who is not a GM making a location) can create their own custom spells or magical items.<br>   Levelling of characters can be incredibly slow as the only method of improvement is by killing other creatures (or, to an exceptionally minor extent, completing quests which usually require the deaths of other creatures).<br>   You can only improve your skills by gaining levels.<br><br>Elder Scrolls 3: Morrowind:<br>   Similar only to previous versions of the Elder Scrolls series (which, for people like myself who've never played the previous version, this is all new).<br>   Open-ended quest system means no storyline, only minor plot elements are apparently to the player, occassionally leading to confusion and aggravation.<br>   Application-based skill system rewards use of skills over &quot;Kill to get better&quot; which is more real-world oriented (who goes out and kills people to get better at craft(woodworking) for crying out loud).<br>   Equipment and spells are similar to known but their application and modularity allow vast variations on a theme, allowing for even greater customization of characters.<br>   Custom spells and magical items are encouraged by the game system (as making them may improve some skills).<br>   Levelling of characters is based on improving the skills in which you have decided your character shall focus in, which will allow you to create a character that levels without engaging in combat, if that's how you choose to play.<br>   You can be trained in skills unrelated to your chosen skills to improve them without having to increase your level to do so.<br><br><br>On the surface, neither game really topples over the other one, it's more a matter of how you play the game. If you like always knowing what you're supposed to do next by being led 'by the nose' (so to speak) then you'll prefer Neverwinter Nights over Morrowind. If you enjoy being given a character and building it however you'd like, outfitting as to your preferrence but occassionally not having any active quests but a lot of room to explore, then you'll prefer Morrowind over Neverwinter Nights. <br>This has been a topic of major discussion in D&amp;D campaigns by DMs for a long time, because we always need to balance our storyline against the wishes of the players and what they want to do. Some players have their own agenda for their characters and as GMs we try to incorporate this into the game, whereas some players have no future planned for their characters and we simply provide them challenges against which they can throw themselves. There isn't any way that a computer or console game can do the necessary &quot;pulling stuff out of your butt&quot; to cover these differences of playing styles (at least, not yet).<br><br>my 2 cents <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.showNextMessage?topicID=99.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.emailToFriend?topicID=99.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.threadControl?topicID=99.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=99.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm13.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=99.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub42.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="ayonaerofrm1">General Forum<option value="ayonaerofrm6">NAG (Nearly Anything Goes)<option value="ayo